\section{GAM overview}

Using these data, a generalized additive mixed model (GAMM) was developed to estimate 
annual growth of western larch, quantified by basal area increment (BAI; Equation ~\ref{eq:bai}): 

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:bai}
BAI = \frac{BA_{m+1}-BA_{m}}{t_{m+1}-t_m}
\end{equation}

, where $BA_m$ refers to tree basal area at measurement $m$ and $t_m$ to the 
unique year of measurement and $m+1$ is a subsequent measurement year.
The choice to annualize BAI was made because re-measurement intervals were inconsistent 
across the data set and annulization allows for flexibility and a finer-scale measure of 
stand dynamics over time \citep{weiskittel2011forest}.

Generalized additive models \citep[GAMs][]{Hastie1990} allow for flexibility in model fitting and an allowance for non-linear 
relationships across variables \citep{Zhao2005,wood2006generalized}. Contrary to traditional 
parametric modeling approaches, GAMs let the data determine the 
shape of the functional relationships by fitting predictor effects with a sum of 
smooth functions of covariates instead of specified parameters \citep{wood2006generalized,Robinson2011}. 
%which also proved beneficial in this case due to the inconsistency of measurement intervals. 
The choice to use a mixed-model approach was made owing to the  
dependence structure that arises from repeat measurements 
on the same trees over time, and thus random effects were specified at the 
individual tree-level. %was it? should it?

%---include something visual about dependence structure?---

GAMMs were fit using the mgcv package \citep{Wood2011} in R \citep{RCoreTeam2021}. 
The mgcv package allows for the specification of smooth functions (or smoothers). 
Smoothers are a sum of fitted estimated basis 
functions that characterize the conditional relationship between the predictor 
and independent variable. They are penalized by a smoothing parameter, which 
constrains a smoother as its complexity grows higher \citep{Pedersen2019}. 
The mgcv package allows smoothing parameters to be estimated via likelihood, information 
theoretical methods, or cross-validation-based methods \citep{wood2006generalized}. 
The maximum likelihood method was used in this study because it allows for 
likelihood-based comparison across models with different fixed terms and smoothing parameters. 
Random effects may also be coded as penalized smooths in this format \citep{Pedersen2019}. 
% , however, 
% when fitting large numbers of intercepts (as done in this study) 
% computation can extremely slow . %%%more here?? do I talk about using both methods since the way random effects are handled with the gamm case is kinda weird? (see pedersen 2019 page 34)
With mgcv, the thin-plate regression spline (TPRS) type
is the default owing to its simple and effective behavior \citep{Wood2003},
and was used for all terms. 
% GAMs in mgcv also allow for 


The model formulation described here was developed with a training 
data set which allowed for varying conditions across all variables. 
Data for two measurement plots out of each stand were withheld for 
the purpose of model validation and assessment.
The model formulation resulting from the selection process described below
was used to evaluate effects of predictors 
on BAI across the entire data set. The formula was also used to assess smooths
across different species mixtures, where the model was re-fit with a subset 
of the training data set where species mixture type was categorized.  
In this case, models were fit using restricted maximum likelihood criteria (REML) 
approach (CITE: patterson and thompson 1971) because it reduces computation time and 
models were not compared in the across-mixture analyses. 
%also reduces bias in variance component estimation

\section{Base model selection}

Predictor selection followed the logic of \cite{Wykoff1990}, 
(\cite{Monserud1996}), and \cite{Vospernik2021} where predictors were 
grouped together based on the following categories: 
(i) size, (ii) density and competition, and (iii) site predictors. 
Size variables considered were tree diameter at breast 
height ($DBH$) and tree basal area ($BA$). 
Density and competition variables considered were: plot basal area ($BAH$), 
plot basal area larger than the subject tree (BAL; expressed as a ratio of BAH), 
plot quadratic mean diameter ($QMD$), ratio of tree DBH to QMD ($D_q$), 
and trees per hectare ($TPH$). Site variables initially considered were: 
slope, aspect, elevation, mean site index, and heatload \citep{Theobald2015}. 
These initial explanatory variables were identified based on availability 
in the PGP data set, whether they could be calculated from the 
available data, and if they have been used in predicting 
BAI in previous empirical modeling efforts. 

% crown competition factor (CCF;\cite{Krajicek1961}), remove??
%-TABLE HERE- table of all variables considered prior to modeling including definitions and how they were calculated?--

A pair-wise collinearity assessment was 
then performed within each group of variables to avoid including 
highly correlated variables together in the model. 
Any predictors with a pair-wise correlation of 
0.7 or higher were not considered in a model together. Although somewhat arbitrary, 
this threshold was selected because a 0.7 correlation indicates that  
variables are closely related. Additionally, variables 
known to represent the same processes, even if not highly linearly correlated 
(such as heatload and aspect, for instance), were not considered together to 
avoid redundancies and reduce model complexity.

GAMs were used to select predictors and visually examine 
predictor partial effects on BAI. % as well as examine residual structure. 
Models were fit in iterations of predictor grouping. 
% including non-correlated variables together 
% respective of grouping while maximizing model accuracy and avoiding overlap. 
The order of this group-wise selection process was based on 
previously identified contributions of these predictor groups 
in estimating BAI \citep{Wykoff1990,Monserud1996}. Highly 
correlated same-group variables were compared in alternative models.
For example, alternative models were fit for both tree DBH 
and BA, selecting whichever best predicted BAI. 
Then, with the selected size variable present in the model, 
competition variables were evaluated and selected 
based on maximizing model accuracy and reducing overlap between variables. 
The same process was used for site variables thereafter, 
finalizing the base model formulation: 

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:baiform}
ln[E(BAI)] = \beta_0 + \sum_j f_{1j}(x_{1j}) + \sum_j f_{2j}(x_{2j}) + \sum_j f_{3j}(x_{3j})\\
\end{equation}

where $ln$ represents the logarithmic link function, $E(BAI)$ represents the expected 
value of BAI, $\beta_0$ represents an intercept, $\sum_j$ represents summation 
of smooth functions for a given group, $x_1$, $x_2$, $x_3$ represent 
size, competition, and site predictor variables, respectively, and $f_1$, $f_2$, $f_3$ 
are smooth functions for each, respectively. 

Root mean squared error (RMSE; Eq. ~\ref{eq:rmse}) was calculated to assess 
model accuracy: 

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:rmse}
RMSE = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_k (\widehat{BAI_k} - BAI_k)^2}{n_{df}}}
\end{equation}

where $\widehat{BAI_k}$ is the model prediction, 
$BAI_k$ is the observed value, and $n_{df}$ is the model residual 
degrees of freedom (number of increments less model effective degrees of freedom).

When comparing models, a model formulation with the lowest RMSE (highest predictive accuracy) 
was selected over alternatives. RMSE was calculated using residual degrees of 
freedom to provide an unbiased estimate. The proportion of null deviance 
explained by the model (or deviance explained) \citep{wood2006generalized} was also 
considered for ensuring acceptable model fit, %Do i even say this?
but was not used as a primary selection criterion. 


\section{Assessing species-mixing impacts on growth}

% - Once a model exists, we can use it on subsets of the data set to 
% determine types of species-mixing effects and their effects on BAI

In order to test for differences in larch growth between different 
species mixtures, distinct mixtures were determined based on species 
proportional share of plot basal area.%BAH. 
To qualify as a specific mixture-type, a minimum of 20\% of the total plot 
basal area had to be in western larch trees and a minimum of 20\% 
in either Douglas-fir or lodgepole pine. This was to ensure that there was a minimal 
representation by both species. To ensure that neither species was  
over-represented in a plot, neither larch nor the other species 
could exceed 65\% of plot BA. Also, both species combined basal area had 
to occupy at least 70\% of total plot BA. 
% This ensured that a range of each mixture-type was captured while prohibiting over-representation of either species within the mixture. 
A pure larch condition was defined as at least 70\% of plot BA in western larch. 

The mgcv package allows for smooth functions that vary across different 
groups \citep{Pedersen2019}. A variation of this method was employed to 
contrast western larch growth across each identified type of mixture against 
the pure larch stand condition. Thus, the identified 
base model formula was fit but where each mixture was allowed an offset for the intercept
and for each smooth term, resulting in a model containing a reference smooth 
for each predictor, and a \emph{difference smooth} for species-mixture 
\citep{wood2006generalized}: 

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:mixes}
\begin{aligned}
ln[E(BAI)] =& \beta_0 + \sum_j f_{j}(x_{j}) + \sum_s \delta_s(\alpha_s + \sum_j g_{j,s}x_j) \\
\delta_s =& 
\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if pure larch}\\
1 & \text{if species mix } s
\end{cases}
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
% \beta_{1j} + f_{j}(x_{n})

where $s$ is a species-mix indicator, $\alpha_s$ is an offset on the intercept 
$\beta_0$ and $g_{j,s}$ is an offset on a smooth for species $s$ and predictor $j$.
These difference smooths were evaluated 
against the pure larch reference smooth using a hypothesis test 
to identify evidence that a difference is non-zero. 
