\section{Comparing species-mixing measures}

Three different species-informed measures were identified for comparison: 
crown competition factor, proportion of basal area occupied by larch, and 
proportion of basal area weighted by species-shade tolerance values. 

Crown competition factor (CCF) is a species-informed density measure that 
is based on tree crown allometry \citep{Krajicek1961}. In this measure, 
each species has an identified maximum crown width in open-grown conditions for 
a given DBH. Crown width is associated with a tree's maximum crown area 
(MCA), and can be estimated as a proportion of stand area using species-specific 
coefficients in a polynomial equation.  
These maximum crown area values are summed within a stand to express 
overall competition for crown space, or CCF:

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:ccf}
CCF = \sum_k w_k h(DBH_k, s_k)
\end{equation}

where $w_k$ is the area expansion factor (TPH) for tree $k$, and $h()$ is a 
function of the DBH of tree $k$, given its species $s$. This study used the 
species-specific coefficient values identified by the FVS-IE variant \citep{Keyser2008}.
This data is normalized such that a CCF value of 100 means that all trees 
in a stand have theoretically achieved their maximum crown area and 
canopy closure is achieved, i.e., any value in excess of 100 
theoretically describes the threshold of competition for crown space. 


