A basal area increment model was specified with the following predictors: 
DBH, crown ratio (CR), basal area larger than the subject (BAL; expressed as a ratio), 
plot basal area (BA), aspect, and a tree-level random effect. 
The model was fit with a gamma distribution family because it allows for 
increasing dispersion in the response variable. A log-link function was chosen 
to ensure that predictions of growth were positive and non-zero.
The model training data set consisted of %training data set?
5,792 basal area increments across 1,975 individual western larch trees. 
The base model RMSE was ~3.34 $\mathrm{cm^2}/yr.$ Fixed effects terms used 
~53 degrees of freedom, and total model deviance explained was 84.9\%. 
Random effects were accounted for using a spline basis 
\citep{wood2006generalized}, and thus had an associated degrees of 
freedom, which was ~1338. Model residual 
degrees of freedom was ~4401. Model statistics are reported in Table 
\ref{tab:rmse}.

Tree DBH and basal area were highly correlated (0.938) and were 
evaluated in separate models. DBH as a predictor yielded higher 
accuracy in predicting BAI than tree BA, with model RMSE values  
of 5.64 $\mathrm{cm^2}/yr.$ and 5.70 $\mathrm{cm^2}/yr.$, respectively. 

Competition variables were partitioned into two sub-groups:  
variables representing a tree's competitive position in a stand, and variables 
that represent the overall competitive environment. Highly collinear variable 
combinations were were TPA-$D_q$ (0.732) and BA-QMD (0.684).  %, CCF-BA (0.95)
Tree-level variables reduced RMSE to 4.50 $\mathrm{cm^2}/yr.$, and then to 
4.31 $\mathrm{cm^2}/yr.$ with plot BA included.

Topographic variables (slope, aspect, elevation) were evaluated as 
potential predictors separately from site index and heatload. Since aspect
is a circular measure, both sin (easting) and cosine (northing) 
transformations were applied as in previous works \citep{Stage1976}. Aspect was best 
accounted for as an interaction term in the form of an isotropic smooth, a 
reduced rank version of thin-plate splines \citep{wood2006generalized}. 
Slope and elevation contributed little to prediction accuracy 
when included with aspect and were associated with concurvity values 
beyond the established threshold. Thus, building on the model and 
comparing aspect, site index, and heatload, aspect was selected as 
the best term, further reducing model RMSE to 4.01 $\mathrm{cm^2}/yr.$

By group, Competition metrics contributed the most in 
deviance explained, followed by size. However, considering 
variables individually, DBH explained more deviance and reduced RMSE 
more than any other variable in the model. 

Partial response curves are shown in Figure \ref{fig:basesmooths}. DBH had an 
overall increasing effect on BAI, eventually tapering at values larger 
than 30cm. Crown ratio was penalized to a near-linear increasing effect that 
was relatively small overall, going from negative to positive at values near 
0.7. BAL showed a modest positive effect which decreased to a slightly 
larger negative effect as western larch became less dominant in a plot. 
Basal area (BA) was represented by an overall decreasing effect, where densities greater 
than 10 $\mathrm{m^2}/ha$ were associated with an increasingly negative effect on growth, 
that tapered off and became less certain at values exceeding 40 $m^2/ha$. As 
aspect varied, the partial effect on growth varied, where positive effects 
were associated with N-NW, N-NE, and NE aspects. NW and SE aspects were associated 
with some negative growth. Data was not sufficient for esimating aspect effects 
for south-facing aspects. 

